      <hedline>
        <hl1>Trade Schools in Decline: The Wrong Message</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Guthrie Alberts letter on June 21 article deplores decline in trade school education in New York City</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>What a tragedy it is that the city's vocational schools are facing declining enrollment (front page, June 21). The trades taught at these schools, including plumbing and carpentry, are in sharp demand and workers in these fields command middle-class salaries.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>What a tragedy it is that the city's vocational schools are facing declining enrollment (front page, June 21). The trades taught at these schools, including plumbing and carpentry, are in sharp demand and workers in these fields command middle-class salaries.</p>
        <p>Perhaps more should be done to promote these schools to both businesses and students. Without them, New York moves closer to becoming a two-tiered city of the rich and the poor.</p>
        <p>GUTHRIE ALBERTS  Brooklyn, June 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
